SIMPLE: rumble
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rumble
<hw>Rum"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>romblen</ets>, akin to D. <ets>rommelen</ets>, G.
<ets>rumpeln</ets>, Dan. <ets>rumle</ets>; cf. Icel. <ets>rymja</ets> to
roar.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a low, heavy, continued sound;
<as>as, the thunder <ex>rumbles</ex> at a distance</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the mean while the skies 'gan <qex>rumble</qex> sore.</q>
<rj><qau>Surrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The people cried and <qex>rombled</qex> up and down.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To murmur; to ripple.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>rumble</qex> gently down with murmur soft.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><--3. to engage in a fight, usu. between street gangs.-->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rumble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rumble
<hw>Rum"ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A noisy report;
rumor.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Delighting ever in <qex>rumble</qex> that is new.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A low, heavy, continuous sound like that made by
heavy wagons or the reverberation of thunder; a confused noise; <as>as,
the <ex>rumble</ex> of a railroad train</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Clamor and <qex>rumble</qex>, and ringing and clatter.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Merged in the <qex>rumble</qex> of awakening day.</q> <rj><qau>H.
James.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A seat for servants, behind the body of a
carriage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Kit, well wrapped, . . . was in the <qex>rumble</qex> behind.</q>
<rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A rotating cask or box in which small articles are
smoothed or polished by friction against each other.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- <col><b>rumble seat</b></col>, <cd>a seat in the rear of an
automobile, outside the passenger cabin, which folds out from the
body.</cd> -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rumble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rumble
<hw>Rum"ble</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to pass through a
rumble, or shaking machine. See <er>Rumble</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
4.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rumbler</ent>⟦br⟧
